Viewed with 3 other birders. Opportunity to identify improved when the entire shorebird flock flushed due to a Peregrine Falcon attack. When they came back to the roost they are all standing tall on alert versus previously when they were tucked in. Easiest to identify within the flock by searching for the one without barring, etc. on the back.

This significantly larger peep was among 15 Least Sandpipers that I believe is Baird's based on long primary projection, lack of droop in bill and buffy color. Would have preferred to have had a Western or two nearby for comparison but that wasn't the case.  Seen at the southernmost shoreline area close to the parking lot.
